John Edward: Key Language Skills for Global Citizens
Scotland’s independent schools retain outstanding academic results and this continued in 2018 with yet another set of outstanding test results, which are only strengthened by individual and collective progress in sports, arts, music and other community engagements.
With up to 30,000 students in Scotland, the schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service for their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further education, their chosen career and their role as global citizens.
As a training sector that can design and implement customized curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and in demand topics in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart.”
It’s a powerful reminder that we can’t just rely on English when we build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
This year’s test results show that language is at the top of the list, with the highest number of approved results in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages received A in the final Higher Grade exam.
Data, collected from SCIS 74 member schools, showed that 72 percent of students who studied Mandarin received an A in Higher Grade, and 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as crucial skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Language as subject selection is now considered to be as important as natural knowledge, technology, engineering and mathematics on curricula in independent schools and beyond.
A survey conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills 2014 found that employers for various reasons had difficulty filling their vacancies, with 17% attributed to a lack of language skills.
With that said, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more future jobs requiring language skills, these skills are becoming necessary in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career choice, they will have a real advantage in the future if they have adopted a second language.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a competitive advantage to a multilingual person.
According to a survey of more than 4,000 adults published by YouGov in 2013, 75 percent responded that they could not speak a foreign language well enough to hold a conversation in it, and there French was the only language that totaled a two-digit percentage (15 percent).
That is why it is so important to invest in language education for our children.
Being able to speak multiple languages, especially those used in developing countries, gives your child a better chance of finding meaningful employment in the future.
In Scotland, each school will learn different combinations of languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while others will teach in languages considered to be most important for the UK by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from within independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and get them with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds on to.
In a global economic environment, it is undoubtedly the language that continues to be crucial for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should really be regarded as "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
