Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump that U.S. leaders highlighted at the U.N. earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korea’s leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the party in this matter were South Korea and not the United States, the Korean peninsula’s nuclear weapons would not have come to such a dead end.”
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was dramatically different than last year when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s future ability to reach the U.S. mainland with missiles was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missileman” on a suicide mission.
This year in the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, thanked Kim for his courage to take action for disarmament, but it said that much work remains and that sanctions must remain until North Korea is disarmed.
